(42, 4, 34, 1, 3, 15, 15, 'thou Jesus of Nazareth', 'Conflict Between Good and Evil', 'This connection highlights the enmity between Jesus, identified as ''the Holy One of God,'' and evil forces, paralleling the conflict described in Genesis 3:15. Both passages emphasize the struggle between divine authority and opposition.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 34, 42, 4, 41, 41, 'thou Jesus of Nazareth', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as the ''Holy One of God'' and ''Christ the Son of God'' by unclean spirits. Both passages emphasize the acknowledgment of Jesus'' divine identity by demons, showcasing their awareness of His authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 35, 42, 4, 41, 41, 'rebuked him', 'Exorcism and Recognition of Christ', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority over demons. In each instance, demons are cast out, acknowledging Jesus as the Christ, highlighting His power and identity.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 35, 40, 8, 26, 26, NULL, 'Authority Over Chaos', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority over chaotic forces. In Luke, He commands a demon to come out, while in Matthew, He rebukes the winds and the sea, demonstrating His power over both spiritual and natural disturbances.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 35, 19, 50, 16, 16, NULL, 'Authority Over Wickedness', 'This connection highlights the authority of God over wickedness. In Luke, Jesus commands the unclean spirit to come out, demonstrating His power, while in Psalms, God questions the wicked about their relationship with His statutes, emphasizing His authority over them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 35, 38, 3, 2, 2, NULL, 'Rebuke of Satan', 'This connection highlights the theme of rebuking Satan in both passages. In Luke, Jesus commands the demon to come out, while in Zechariah, the Lord rebukes Satan directly.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 35, 41, 3, 11, 12, 'come out of him', 'Authority over Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority over unclean spirits. In Luke, Jesus commands the spirit to come out, while in Mark, the spirits recognize him as the Son of God and submit to his authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 35, 41, 9, 26, 26, 'come out of him', 'Connection of Demonic Exorcism', 'Both passages emphasize the dramatic expulsion of evil spirits from individuals. In Luke, the spirit is commanded to ''come out of him,'' while in Mark, the spirit''s departure leaves the boy appearing lifeless.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 35, 42, 8, 24, 24, 'rebuked', 'Authority Over Chaos', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' authority to rebuke chaos, whether it be a demon or nature. This connection highlights His power to bring calm in tumultuous situations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 36, 42, 4, 32, 32, NULL, 'Authority and Power in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the authority and power of Jesus'' words. In Luke 4:32, his doctrine astonishes the listeners, while in Luke 4:36, his command over unclean spirits showcases that same power.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 36, 40, 12, 22, 23, 'they were all amazed', 'Authority and Power in Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement of the people at Jesus'' authority in healing and casting out unclean spirits. The phrase ''all the people were amazed'' in Matthew parallels the amazement expressed in Luke, highlighting the impact of Jesus'' miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 36, 41, 1, 27, 27, NULL, 'Authority Over Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the authority Jesus has over unclean spirits, leading to amazement among the people. The similar phrasing regarding his command over these spirits highlights a shared theme of divine power.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 36, 41, 7, 37, 37, 'What a word is this!', 'Authority and Astonishment in Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the amazement of the people at Jesus'' miraculous works. In Luke, the crowd is astonished by His authority over unclean spirits, while in Mark, they are astonished by His ability to heal the deaf and dumb.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 36, 42, 10, 17, 20, 'with authority and power he commandeth', 'Authority Over Unclean Spirits', 'This connection highlights the authority given to Jesus and later to the seventy disciples over unclean spirits. Both passages emphasize the power to command evil forces, showcasing a continuity in the theme of divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 36, 44, 19, 12, 16, 'with authority and power he commandeth', 'Authority Over Evil Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the authority over unclean spirits. In Luke, Jesus commands the spirits with power, while in Acts, the evil spirit recognizes Jesus and Paul, highlighting the significance of divine authority in exorcism.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 36, 60, 3, 22, 22, 'with authority and power he commandeth', 'Authority Over Spiritual Powers', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority over unclean spirits and powers. Both passages emphasize the power of Jesus, with Luke noting his command over unclean spirits and 1 Peter stating that authorities and powers are made subject to him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 37, 41, 1, 45, 45, 'the fame of him went out', 'Spread of Jesus'' Fame', 'Both passages emphasize the widespread fame of Jesus. In Luke, it states that ''the fame of him went out,'' while Mark describes how this fame led to people coming to him from ''every quarter.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 37, 42, 4, 14, 14, 'fame of him went out', 'Connection of Fame in Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of Jesus'' fame in Galilee. The phrase ''fame of him went out'' appears in both verses, highlighting the growing recognition of Jesus'' ministry.', 'keyword', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 37, 23, 52, 13, 13, 'fame of him went out', 'Fame and Exaltation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of exaltation found in both passages. In Luke, the fame of Jesus suggests a rising prominence, while Isaiah speaks of a servant who will be exalted and extolled.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 37, 40, 4, 23, 25, 'the fame of him went out', 'Connection of Fame and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of Jesus'' fame as he performed miracles and healed the sick. This connection highlights how his reputation grew as he preached and healed throughout the regions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 37, 40, 9, 26, 26, 'fame of him went out', 'Connection of Fame in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of fame regarding Jesus'' ministry. This connection highlights how His reputation reached various regions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 37, 41, 6, 14, 14, NULL, 'Spread of Fame and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the spread of Jesus'' fame as noted in Luke, which directly influences Herod''s perception of him in Mark. Both passages emphasize the impact of Jesus'' reputation on those around him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 38, 40, 8, 14, 15, 'Simon’s wife’s mother was taken with a great fever', 'Healing of Peter''s Mother-in-Law', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus entering Peter''s house and finding his wife''s mother sick with a fever. They describe the healing event where Jesus touches her hand, leading to her recovery.', 'parallel', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 38, 41, 1, 29, 31, 'Simon’s wife’s mother was taken with a great fever', 'Healing of Simon''s Mother-in-Law', 'Both passages emphasize Simon’s wife’s mother being sick with a fever and the subsequent healing by Jesus. This connection highlights the miraculous nature of Jesus'' ministry as he responds to the needs of those close to his disciples.', 'parallel', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 38, 43, 11, 22, 22, 'besought him for her', 'Healing and Intercession', 'This connection highlights the theme of intercession for healing. In Luke, Simon''s family seeks Jesus'' help for the sick, while in John, the speaker expresses confidence in Jesus'' ability to ask God for assistance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 38, 59, 5, 14, 15, NULL, 'Healing and Prayer Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing through prayer. In Luke, Jesus is sought for healing, while James instructs the sick to call for prayer from church elders.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 38, 40, 15, 23, 23, 'besought him', 'Appeal for Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the act of beseeching Jesus for help. In Luke, Simon''s companions ask for healing for his mother-in-law, while in Matthew, the disciples request Jesus to send away a woman who is crying out for assistance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 38, 42, 7, 3, 4, 'besought him for her', 'Healing and Intercession', 'This connection highlights the theme of intercession for healing in both passages. In Luke 4:38, Simon''s family beseeches Jesus for healing, while in Luke 7:3-4, the elders beseech Jesus on behalf of a servant.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 4, 38, 43, 11, 3, 3, NULL, 'Sickness and Healing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of sickness and the urgency of seeking help. Both passages emphasize the need for intervention when someone is ill, as seen in Simon''s mother and Lazarus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
